\f0\b\fs42 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs40 \cf0 Heat the blackberries, sugar, and water in a small pot over medium-high heat. While warming, smash with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/potato/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 potato}} masher, until a thick even consistency is reached, about 8 minutes.\
Pour the blackberries through a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sieve/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sieve}}, into a bowl, pushing some flesh through with the juices, making sure to catch the seeds. Cool in the refrigerator for at least 10 minutes.\
Fill a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cocktail/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cocktail}} shaker with 2 tablespoons of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/blackberry/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 blackberry}} puree, 2 tablespoons of the mint leaves, 2 ounces of gin, 1 tablespoon lime juice, and a handful of ice. Shake vigorously 5 to 6 times until the drink is ice cold. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/strain/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Strain}} the mixture into a tall glass. Top with 6 ounces of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/ginger-ale/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ginger ale}} and stir lightly. Repeat for the remaining 3 servings. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/finish/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Finish}} and serve with a scoop of sorbet or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/ice-cream/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ice cream}}.\
